SIMPLE: cognizable
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Cognizable
<hw>Cog"ni*za*ble</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ <?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>connaissable</ets>, fr. <ets>conna⟦icir⟧tre</ets> to know, L.
<ets>cognoscere</ets>. See Cognition.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Capable of
being known or apprehended; <as>as, <ex>cognizable</ex>
causes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fitted to be a subject of judicial investigation;
capable of being judicially heard and determined.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Cognizable</qex> both in the ecclesiastical and secular
courts.</q> <rj><qau>Ayliffe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cognizably</ent>⟦br⟧
